Comments before doing any operations:

  1. Drop columns: We just have 2 (numerical) columns with nan values. Knowing the fact that we have 552 columns, 550 of which are numerical doesn't matter if we just skip this 2 columns for the analysis.

  2. Drop rows: Also we could think that we just have (100+100 <= 200) rows with Nan values and 2000 rows. Dropping them is an option but now we are talking about around 10% of the data which it's a considerable amount.

  3. Fillna: Another option is to fill our numerical Nan values with some sort of mean, median, ... value.

I'm going to choose to choose fillna as there are not many nan values, which they are not going to affect much in their own column, but instead I dont want to get rid of all the other data just for a few Nan values in one column/row. Before selecting the function I'm going to analyse the columns data distribution (as we just have 2) and then select the best option.

Since the data is right-skewed, using the median might be more appropriate to fill in NaN values. The median is more robust against skewed data, as the mean would be biased toward the tail of the distribution.

4. Outlier Detection¶

Outliers can heavily influence statistical measures and models. We will detect them using Z-scores and possibly remove those who are more than 3 std away from the mean and see how much data we'll keep.

This z-scores are meant to be used if the data follows a normal distribution, which we are just assuming it is. Probably is not, or at least not all the columns so we're not going to get good results...

In [138]:
from scipy import stats

# Detect outliers using Z-score
z_scores = np.abs(stats.zscore(data))
outliers = (z_scores > 3)

# Remove rows where any feature has an outlier value
df_no_outliers = data[(outliers == False).all(axis=1)]

print(f"Data shape before removing outliers: {data.shape}")
print(f"Data shape after removing outliers: {df_no_outliers.shape}")

Data shape before removing outliers: (2000, 550)
Data shape after removing outliers: (657, 550)

We're dropping 67% of the data $\left(\frac{2000-657}{2000} = 0.67 \right)$ using this method! This isn't practical for real-world analysis, as it results in analyzing only a small portion of the data.

A better approach is to treat each row as a single data point and calculate multidimensional z-scores. This makes more sense because analyzing features individually ignores the relationships between them. For instance, an outlier in column $n_k$ might not be an outlier when considering the other features together. The multidimensional analysis considers the entire context, identifying true outliers by evaluating each row as a unique entity.

In [139]:

As we can see, there aren't many negative correlations, but there are a large number of strong positive correlations (thousands of feature pairs with over 95% correlation). If two variables are more than 95% correlated, they essentially provide the same information. So...

Why Drop One of Highly Correlated Variables?

  1. Redundancy: When two variables are highly correlated, they carry similar information about the variance in the data. Keeping both doesn't add much value and can lead to redundancy.

  2. Multicollinearity: In regression models or algorithms sensitive to feature collinearity (like linear regression), high correlation between features can cause multicollinearity. This can make the model's coefficients unstable and harder to interpret.

  3. Simplicity: Reducing the number of features simplifies the model, making it easier to interpret and potentially faster to train.

  4. Overfitting: In some cases, highly correlated features can lead to overfitting, where the model learns the noise in the training data rather than the underlying pattern.

This brings us to the 'dimension reduction' section, where we'll use more advanced methods. For now, consider this a basic example of how we can reduce dimensions in our data. More complex algorithms can take this even further. But first, let's do a quick demonstration of how we can safely remove some columns without losing important information.

It's a tricky algorithm because the pairs overlap, so we need to be careful when dropping values. First, we'll gather all pairs with more than 95% correlation. After collecting them, we'll drop the pairs one by one in a specific order. In a while loop, we'll pick a pair, choose one value to keep and the other to drop. Then, we'll remove every pair related to the value we're keeping. We'll repeat this process until all pairs are handled.

In [145]:
c95 = np.array(corr_list[np.abs(corr_list) > 0.95].sort_values(ascending=False).index.tolist())
c95_values = set(c95.flatten())
c95 = pd.DataFrame({"p1":c95[:,0], "p2":c95[:,1]})

dropping_columns = set()
maintain_columns = set()
    
while len(c95) > 0:

    index = c95.index[0]

    if c95["p1"][index] in dropping_columns:
        if c95["p2"][index] in dropping_columns:
            c95 = c95.drop(index=[index])
            continue
        else:
            name = c95["p2"][index]
            name_toDrop = c95["p1"][index]
    else:
        name = c95["p1"][index]
        name_toDrop = c95["p2"][index]

    maintain_columns.add(name)
    dropping_columns.add(name_toDrop)

    s1 = set(c95["p2"][c95["p1"] == name].values.tolist())
    s2 = set(c95["p1"][c95["p2"] == name].values.tolist())
    s = s1.union(s2)
    dropping_columns = dropping_columns.union(s)

    c95 = c95[(c95["p1"] != name) & (c95["p2"] != name)]

final_drops = c95_values - maintain_columns
len(final_drops)
Out[145]:
245

With this result we would get rid of 245 columns, just by deleting the columns that has more than 95% correlation between each other (represents basically the same data as the other columns that we maintain). That's a huge improvement in this dataset as we are deleting almost 50% of the data (that seems not to be very useful) which is going to help to create better predictive models on the future.

7. Dimensionality reduction¶

Principal Component Analysis (PCA)¶

PCA helps in dimensionality reduction by finding linear combinations of variables that explain the most variance. First we are going to reduce the data by setting our PCA to explain 95% of the data variance, therefore we wont lose too much data-meaning and in the other side we'll significantly reduce our number of dimensions.

In order to have a PCA visualixation we'll plot the best 2 of this selected components.

In [150]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

# Apply PCA
pca = PCA(0.95)
pca_result = pca.fit_transform(scaled_data)
print(pca_result.shape)

# Plot PCA result, color by target property
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
plt.scatter(pca_result[:, 0], pca_result[:, 1], c=data[y], cmap='viridis')
plt.colorbar(label=y)
plt.xlabel('PCA 1')
plt.ylabel('PCA 2')
plt.title('PCA 2D Plot')
plt.show()

(2000, 60)

We ended up with just 60 components, which is an excellent result as we managed to retain 95% of the total variance. At the same time, we reduced the dimensionality by 86% $\left(\frac{449-60}{449}\right)$, effectively removing features that are likely not useful for future predictive models. In the following plot, we can see the variance explained by each PCA component. I also want to highlight that 80% of the variance is covered by only the first 18 principal components, which is an incredible improvement. However, keeping just those 18 would be too lenient, and I wanted to avoid losing too many features, so we opted to retain more components for a more comprehensive analysis.

8. Conclusion¶

This exploratory data analysis (EDA) provided a comprehensive examination of a complex dataset, df, with over 500 features and 2000 observations. We began by identifying and correcting data type issues, particularly focusing on object-type columns that contained numeric data but had some non-numeric entries. By cleaning these columns and converting them to the correct data type, we ensured a more consistent dataset for subsequent analyses.

In the process of handling missing values, we opted to isolate the numerical data into a new DataFrame, data. We discuss different strategies for managing the missing values, including filling them with median values and dropping rows or columns where appropriate. This preprocessing step was crucial in maintaining the integrity of the dataset.

For outlier detection, we employed Z-scores to identify and handle outliers. By exploring both unidimensional and multidimensional Z-scores, we were able to refine our detection process and identify a more reasonable number of outliers, minimizing the risk of removing too many legitimate observations. This step helped to reduce the impact of extreme values on subsequent analyses. The resultant data frame was called data_cleaned.

Moving to the correlation analysis, we discovered a significant number of highly correlated features, with more than 95% correlation. To mitigate multicollinearity, we removed these highly correlated features, resulting in the elimination of 245 columns, final_drops, roughly 50% of the dataset. This reduction was essential in simplifying the dataset and improving the performance of any models that might be built in the future.

We also investigated the correlation, corr, between the features and the target variable, experimental_proprty. This involved not only exploring linear correlations but also examining quadratic relationships by transforming the features. This deeper look at potential associations provided a better understanding of the relationships within the dataset.

Finally, we applied dimensionality reduction techniques to visualize the dataset and uncover underlying patterns. Using Principal Component Analysis (PCA) and t-Distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE), we initially reduced the dataset to two dimensions for visualization purposes, allowing us to identify clusters and trends within the data. This strict reduction was specifically for visualization; in a real modeling scenario, we would reduce the dimensions only to a level that preserves the meaningful variance in the data while still allowing for manageable input sizes. In practice, as we did with PCA, we retained 60 components instead of just two, ensuring that we maintained a balance between dimensionality reduction and the interpretability of the data. This approach would similarly apply to using the t-SNE algorithm in a modeling context.

In summary, this EDA involved a series of methodical steps to clean, process, and explore the dataset, culminating in a more manageable set of features and a better understanding of the relationships within the data. By addressing data quality issues, handling outliers, reducing dimensionality, and exploring correlations, we have prepared the dataset for more advanced analyses and potential modeling.
